Harlubuus-the occurrence at the end of the Suetonius of a remarkable note, in the hand of rba copyist, Hic antiquissimum exemplar finit et hoc integrum araur. Taken along with indications which go to show that the original of H must have been a MS. abounding in contractions, this must be held to render it probable that it was no mere copy that Enoch brought back with him to Italy, but his original ‘find-the Hersfeld codex-probably of the thirteenth century. lf this inference is correct, a lineal descent may be established for H from the archetype of Fulda

Perhaps the most striking internal characteristic of H is its frequent agreement with the hand in the Ladensis known as b (see p. lxx). If b is as late as is generally supposed, the probability is that its readings were derived from H, or from some similar copy executed about the same time. For‘proof of this agreement, reference might be made to the critical notes, but it may be instructive to exhibit here some of the resemblances referred to, as well as some of the differences between the two traditions.
